Let $h$ be the height of the cone.  Then by similar triangles, we have
\[\frac{r}{h} = \frac{r - 6\sqrt{3}}{h - 6\sqrt{3}}.\]Solving for $r$ gives $r = \frac{h}{2} + 3\sqrt{3}.$

Since the sphere is tangent to the sides of the cone, $A,$ $B,$ and $P$ are collinear.  Thus, $AP + BP = AB = 12\sqrt{3},$ so $2r = AP + BP + AB = 12\sqrt{3},$ which means $r = 6\sqrt{3}.$

Let $S$ be the center of the sphere.  Then $OS = r,$ and $OP = h - r = h - 6\sqrt{3}.$  By the Pythagorean Theorem on right triangle $OSP,$
\[h^2 - 12h\sqrt{3} + 108 = 36.\]Then $h^2 - 12h\sqrt{3} + 72 = 0,$ which factors as $(h - 6\sqrt{3})^2 = 0.$  Hence, $h = 6\sqrt{3}.$

[asy]
import three;

size(180);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple A, B, O, P, V, S;

A = (-1,0,1.5);
B = (1,0,1.5);
V = (0,0,-3);
O = (0,0,0);
P = (0,0,1.5 - sqrt(3)/2);
S = (0,0,1.5 - 2 * sqrt(3));

draw(surface(A--O--B--cycle),paleyellow,nolight);
draw(surface(O--A--P--cycle),paleyellow,nolight);
draw(surface(O--B--P--cycle),paleyellow,nolight);
draw(surface(S--P--A--cycle),paleyellow,nolight);
draw(surface(S--P--B--cycle),paleyellow,nolight);
draw(O--A--B--cycle);
draw(O--P);
draw(A--P);
draw(B--P);
draw(S--P);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, N);
label("$O$", O, S);
label("$P$", P, S);
label("$V$", V, N);
label("$S$", S, S);
[/asy]

The volume of the sphere is then
\[\frac{4}{3} \pi r^3 = \frac{4}{3} \pi (6\sqrt{3})^3 = \boxed{432 \pi}.\]
